He also made the acquaintance of Seneca, but later on in his life and in the expressive words of the biographer ‘non ut caperetur ejus ingenio.' And it would have been strange had it been otherwise, for, as Jahn well points out, there could be little unanimity of fe'eling between two men who had nothing in common beyond the profession of the same philosophical principles. It is true that Seneca writes like Persius, and that his works form the best possible commentary on the Satires, but with this all resemblance ceases between the two men.
